│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash is an assertion failure in isSingleSourceMaskImpl: it asserts that  │
│ each shuffle mask element must be within [0, NumOpElts*2). In our reproducer, │
│ VectorCombine::foldInsExtVectorToShuffle, when handling a length-changing     │
│ combine (source <16 x i8> to destination <4 x i8>), constructs an             │
│ ExtToVecMask for a SK_PermuteSingleSrc cost query with a mask element set to  │
│ 11 (the extract index) while using Ty = <4 x i8>. This is out of bounds for   │
│ the 4-lane context used by TargetTransformInfo's improveShuffleKindFromMask   │
│ (NumSrcElts=4), causing the assertion.                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ - The pass visits the insertelement and immediately crashes during cost       │
│ modeling (no IR changed yet).                                                 │
│ - Backtrace shows the crash originates from improveShuffleKindFromMask        │
│ calling ShuffleVectorInst::isReverseMask, which calls isSingleSourceMaskImpl  │
│ and asserts on the mask element value.                                        │
│ - The problematic query is TTI.getShuffleCost(SK_PermuteSingleSrc,            │
│ DstVecTy=<4 x i8>, ExtToVecMask=[11, poison, poison, poison]).                │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ - improveShuffleKindFromMask assumes the operand size equals the result       │
│ vector size (it uses Ty->getElementCount() to compute NumSrcElts). This is    │
│ stated in the helper functions ("We don't have vector operand size            │
│ information, so assume operands are the same size as the mask").              │
│ - VectorCombine, however, passed a mask containing an element (11) larger     │
│ than 2*NumDstElts-1 for the SK_PermuteSingleSrc cost query when modeling a    │
│ length-changing shuffle. This makes the mask invalid for TTI’s classification │
│ helpers and triggers the assertion.                                           │
│ - Therefore, the bug is in VectorCombine’s cost modeling: it must not pass    │
│ out-of-range mask indices to TTI when Ty is the smaller destination vector.   │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                     │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp                       │
│ - Location: In VectorCombine::foldInsExtVectorToShuffle, in the               │
│ NeedExpOrNarrow path where ExtToVecMask is prepared for the                   │
│ SK_PermuteSingleSrc cost query.                                               │
│ - Change: When ExtIdx is out of bounds for NumDstElts, clamp the mask index   │
│ into the legal range for Ty to avoid out-of-bounds indices in TTI             │
│ classification.                                                               │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit:                                                                         │
│ - Before: ExtToVecMask[0] = ExtIdx;                                           │
│ - After:  ExtToVecMask[0] = static_cast<int>(ExtIdx % NumDstElts);            │
│                                                                               │
│ Rationale: This guarantees the mask indices are within [0, NumDstElts-1] for  │
│ the single-source cost query, satisfying isSingleSourceMaskImpl. It preserves │
│ the intent of modeling a generic length-changing shuffle cost without relying │
│ on operand sizes that TTI does not see. Broadcasting or generic permute       │
│ classification remains acceptable for cost modeling; importantly, it avoids   │
│ the assertion while keeping costs conservative.                               │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By clamping the out-of-range mask element when NeedExpOrNarrow is true, we    │
│ prevent TTI’s improveShuffleKindFromMask from asserting on invalid indices.   │
│ This fix keeps cost modeling valid and allows the transformation to proceed   │
│ or be rejected based on cost without crashing. The functional IR remains      │
│ unchanged; only the internal cost query mask is sanitized.                    │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
